Carpites walcotti Dorf, n. sp. (Plate 19, Figs. 1, 2)

Phyllites trillioides Dorf, n. sp. (Plate 17, Fig. 3)

There are but 2 incomplete specimens of this type in the collections. The general outline, venation, and heart-shaped base are typical of the leaves usually referred to Smilax. In modern leaves of Smilax, however, 1 have never seen forking primary veins such as are present in these fossil specimens. The leaves of Tr'z'llz'una on the other hand, are almost always characterized by forking primaries (cf. T. cernuum Linne).³ In the absence of more complete material, however, it 15 impossible to make a definite generic reference.

These specimens resemble both smilax? inquirenda Knowlton from the Laramie formation 4 and S. carbonensis Cockercll from the Hanna formation.⁵ There are enough characters preserved, however, to indicate that they are not conspecific with either.

Occurrence—Craig, Colorado‚ Loc. P. 375.
